{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568270"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:12:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:12:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19715"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19715"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.21,0.02,0.02,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87136"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12493"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71395"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8164"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45081"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87136"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless swelling just in front of her left armpit. She says this has been present for a few years but has become more noticeable since puberty. She is concerned about its appearance. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a soft, mobile, non-tender mass measuring 3 cm in the left anterior axillary fold. The mass becomes more prominent when she raises her arm (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Accessory breast tissue","Lipoma","Lymphadenopathy","Sebaceous cyst","Fibroadenoma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic case of accessory breast tissue, also known as polymastia. \u003Cstrong\u003EAccessory breast tissue\u003C/strong\u003E occurs along the embryological milk line, which extends from the axilla to the groin. The most common location is in the axillary region. It typically becomes more noticeable during puberty due to hormonal stimulation and may enlarge during pregnancy or lactation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elipoma\u003C/strong\u003E would be a possibility in this location, but these are less commonly seen in teenagers and would not typically show hormonal responsiveness. Lipomas are also more likely to be found in other subcutaneous locations rather than specifically along the milk line.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E would be unlikely to present as a chronic, asymptomatic swelling. Enlarged lymph nodes are typically more firm and discrete, and there would usually be an underlying cause such as infection or inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esebaceous cyst\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present as a dome-shaped lesion with a central punctum and would not follow the distribution of the milk line. They are also uncommon in teenagers and are more typically found on the face, neck, or trunk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Efibroadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E is common in this age group, these typically occur within existing breast tissue rather than in the axillary region. They also tend to be firmer and more well-circumscribed on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of accessory breast tissue depends on symptoms. If asymptomatic, reassurance may be sufficient. If the tissue is causing physical or psychological distress, surgical excision can be considered. The tissue should be monitored similarly to normal breast tissue as it can undergo the same pathological changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Accessory breast tissue commonly presents along the embryological milk line from axilla to groin.","Accessory breast tissue typically becomes noticeable during puberty and may enlarge during pregnancy.","Most cases of accessory breast tissue are asymptomatic and can be managed conservatively unless causing symptoms."],"references":["Mareti E, Vatopoulou A, Spyropoulou G-A, et al. Breast Disorders in Adolescence: A Review of the Literature. Breast Care 2021; 16:149\u201355"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71395"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19715"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21695"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21695"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/zSoZf6MEKiNfgploUk8NprN8O9ugEZ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/zSoZf6MEKiNfgploUk8NprN8O9ugEZ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":300,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71395"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-26T17:22:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T19:20:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12493"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87136"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type